org.jimmutable.core.serialization.reader

Class ObjectParseTree

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jimmutable.core.serialization.reader.ObjectParseTree
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<ObjectParseTree>

    public final class ObjectParseTree
extends Object
implements Iterable<ObjectParseTree>
    ObjectParseTree is created by Parser and used by StandardObject(s) to instantiate themselves from serialized data. ObjectParseTree are mutable (they are modified by Parser and Builder). That being said, one should not modify a parse tree without a really good reason (generally, use builder to do this)
    Author:
    jim.kane

      • deserialize

        public static Object deserialize(String document)
        Construct an object from previously serialized data. The format is automatically detected. There are two common exceptions that can occur when constructing an object from previously serialized data, SerializeException (trouble reading) and ValidationException (object read was not valid). Both extend RuntimeException, so you are not required to handle them explicitly. That being said, most (nee all) well designed readers of serialized data "trap" errors: thought must be given as to what to do when this happens.
        Parameters:
        document - The data to read from
        Returns:
        The object previously serialized

      • registerTypeName

        public static void registerTypeName(Class c)
        Register a type name. TypeName(s) must be registered *prior* to readign any instances of the type. It is safe to register a TypeName multiple times (last registration wins). The function is thread safe. Typically, each Jimmtuable VM implements a register class (See JimmutableTypeNameRegister). Rember to invoke this (pretty much first thing) at boot time. Classes must have a static public method named TYPE_NAME to be registered
        Parameters:
        c - The class to register
